  "texts": [
    "In the Taylor expansion of Γ(z) near an insertion point z k, we learnt in equation (4.5) thata k = n-2+2g α=1 W (u α) i̸ =k V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i) V w k m k 1 -1/2,m k 2 -1/2 (x k; z k) n-2+2g α=1 W (u α) n i=1 V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i),is the coefficient of the first non-vanishing term after the constant.",
    "This coefficient is a property of the covering map, so is determined by the data {x i, w i, z i } and is therefore independent of {m i 1, m i 2 }.",
    "This means we can apply this formula recursively to deducen-2+2g α=1 W (u α) n i=1 V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i) = 1 (a k) s n-2+2g α=1 W (u α) i̸ =k V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i) V w k m k 1 -s/2,m k 2 -s/2,for any integer s. Definingh i = m i 1 + m i 2 + w i /2, this leads to our final result n-2+2g α=1 W (u α) n i=1 V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i) = Γ W Γ n i=1 a Γ i -h i n-3+3g I=1 δ(f Γ I),(4.9) JHEP04(2024)048where W Γ are undetermined ordinary functions of the fixed points in moduli space for the covering map Γ and {x i, w i }.",
    "28 The constants a Γ i are precisely those given by (4.5), except that we also acknowledge precisely where we are in moduli space by labelling them with the corresponding covering map.As was mentioned earlier, this localisation to covering maps (4.9) was previously argued using the following incidence relation: whenever a covering map exists, it is shown in [7] that(ξ -(z) + Γ(z)ξ + (z)) n-2 α=1 W (u α) n i=1 V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i) = 0.",
